The user wants me to implement an LRU (Least Recently Used) Cache in TypeScript. The spec mentions ALG-2 and says:
- O(1) get/put operations
- Export everything the spec says to export

An LRU Cache typically:
1. Has a maximum capacity
2. When capacity is exceeded, removes the least recently used item
3. Has get and put operations that are O(1)
4. Moving an item to the "most recently used" when accessed

To achieve O(1) operations, I need:
- A Map for O(1) lookups
- A doubly-linked list to maintain order (most recent at head, least recent at tail)

Standard implementation:
- `get(key)`: O(1) lookup, move to front
- `put(key, value)`: O(1) insert/update, move to front, evict LRU if needed

Since the spec says "Export everything the spec says to export" but doesn't explicitly list what to export, I should implement a reasonable LRU cache class/interface. The typical export would be a class or function that creates an LRU cache.

Let me implement this with:
- A class `LRUCache<K, V>` with constructor taking capacity
- `get(key: K): V | undefined`
- `put(key: K, value: V): void`

I'll use a Map for O(1) lookups and a doubly-linked list node structure for maintaining the order.

Actually, JavaScript Map maintains insertion order but not access order, so I need a doubly-linked list.

Here's a standard implementation:

```typescript
export class LRUCache<K, V> {
  private capacity: number;
  private cache: Map<K, Node<K, V>>;
  private head: Node<K, V>;
  private tail: Node<K, V>;

  constructor(capacity: number) {
    this.capacity = capacity;
    this.cache = new Map();
    this.head = new Node<K, V>(undefined as any, undefined as any);
    this.tail = new Node<K, V>(undefined as any, undefined as any);
    this.head.next = this.tail;
    this.tail.prev = this.head;
  }

  get(key: K): V | undefined {
    if (!this.cache.has(key)) return undefined;
    const node = this.cache.get(key)!;
    this.moveToHead(node);
    return node.value;
  }

  put(key: K, value: V): void {
    if (this.cache.has(key)) {
      const node = this.cache.get(key)!;
      node.value = value;
      this.moveToHead(node);
    } else {
      const newNode = new Node(key, value);
      this.cache.set(key, newNode);
      this.addToHead(newNode);
      if (this.cache.size > this.capacity) {
        const lruNode = this.tail.prev!;
        this.removeNode(lruNode);
        this.cache.delete(lruNode.key);
      }
    }
  }

  private moveToHead(node: Node<K, V>): void {
    this.removeNode(node);
    this.addToHead(node);
  }

  private addToHead(node: Node<K, V>): void {
    node.next = this.head.next;
    node.prev = this.head;
    this.head.next!.prev = node;
    this.head.next = node;
  }

  private removeNode(node: Node<K, V>): void {
    node.prev!.next = node.next;
    node.next!.prev = node.prev;
  }
}

class Node<K, V> {
  key: K;
  value: V;
  next: Node<K, V> | null = null;
  prev: Node<K, V> | null = null;

  constructor(key: K, value: V) {
    this.key = key;
    this.value = value;
  }
}
```

This implementation uses sentinel head and tail nodes to simplify edge cases. The `put` method handles both updating existing keys and adding new ones, evicting the least recently used item when capacity is exceeded. The `get` method returns the value and moves the accessed node to the front.

